and I could see they were just
terrified and just had no idea

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:51.610
if I was going to know what
to say or start spouting off

00:44:51.610 --> 00:44:53.450
about Rembrandt or something.

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:59.790
And it was hard, but I did
memorize a lot in my life

00:44:59.790 --> 00:45:04.950
so I was able to talk about
strike fighters as much

00:45:04.950 --> 00:45:10.220
as about Rembrandt, and I did
find that being able to make

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:15.440
that connection as someone
who had spent my career

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:17.450
up until then trying to
understand the culture

00:45:17.450 --> 00:45:21.840
of the country where I was
serving, that meant so much

00:45:21.840 --> 00:45:26.000
to the Dutch so that I was
able to take, you know,

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.600
the Prime Minister and
the Foreign Minister

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:33.670
around their own museums and
show them their exhibitions.

00:45:33.670 --> 00:45:39.000
I also did that with
my own embassy staff.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.290
There were some great
Rembrandt exhibitions and stuff,

00:45:41.290 --> 00:45:45.430
so I got them all in when
the museums were closed and,

00:45:45.430 --> 00:45:48.430
you know, was able to introduce
them to the local culture

00:45:48.430 --> 00:45:53.910
as well, and I just would
mention that I also had,

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:56.160
every ambassador has, it
was a wonderful privilege

00:45:56.160 --> 00:45:59.410
to have a collection
of art in the embassy.

00:45:59.410 --> 00:46:01.520
Some go with their own
personal collections.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:05.120
I did not have one and did
not do that, but with the help

00:46:05.120 --> 00:46:07.710
of the fantastic bureau
at the State Department

00:46:07.710 --> 00:46:09.940
that supports this program,

00:46:09.940 --> 00:46:14.450
I was able to identify just
really fantastic works of art

00:46:14.450 --> 00:46:16.900
that in one way or another
showed the connection

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:18.820
between the Netherlands
and the United States

00:46:18.820 --> 00:46:23.680
from the Calder Mobile in the
front hall to Claes Oldenburg

00:46:23.680 --> 00:46:25.270
to William De Kooning as well

00:46:25.270 --> 00:46:30.000
as the great Rembrandt Peale
portrait of Thomas Jefferson

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.440
and you know, that was a regular
part of when people would come

00:46:32.440 --> 00:46:34.870
to the residence, I
would give them the tour

00:46:34.870 --> 00:46:38.060
and they would walk in and they
could see they may not know what

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:42.130
the works of were but they could
see right way that connection

00:46:42.130 --> 00:46:43.870
and they loved seeing
that connection.

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:46.230
You know, they'd say wow a
new American artist thought

00:46:46.230 --> 00:46:47.920
that much about Holland.

00:46:47.920 --> 00:46:51.600
After, I'll just leave you
with one story of the impact

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:54.550
of culture, and this was
on someone who worked

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:57.110
at the embassy, I love this.

00:46:57.110 --> 00:47:00.360
I left in June, 2001 so I
wasn't there for the fourth

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:04.730
of July party and someone I
encountered later in July said,

00:47:04.730 --> 00:47:06.600
oh my gosh, I was just
at your residence,

00:47:06.600 --> 00:47:10.410
I was there for the fourth
of July party and a member

00:47:10.410 --> 00:47:14.650
of your staff gave a me a tour
of the collection that you had.

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:17.490
And I said, but it was
gone, all the paintings

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:21.150
and sculptures had been sent
back to their owners by then,

00:47:21.150 --> 00:47:24.600
and the person said, yes
that's right, but the person

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:27.360
from your staff loved
that collection so much

00:47:27.360 --> 00:47:30.280
that they took me through
the house and said,

00:47:30.280 --> 00:47:34.300
this is what used to hang here,
and this is what it looked like

00:47:34.300 --> 00:47:36.830
and this is why it was there.

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:41.710
So, that was one of my favorite
public diplomacy actions.

00:47:44.340 --> 00:47:49.340
&gt;&gt; Yes, thank you very much
for your presentations,

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:53.030
I found them very fascinating.

