01:01:59.370 --> 01:02:02.270
&gt;&gt; So this for both Amy Storrow
and Ambassador Schneider.

01:02:02.270 --> 01:02:05.090
I'm wondering, from
being out in the field,

01:02:05.090 --> 01:02:07.370
did you see other countries
doing cultural diplomacy,

01:02:07.370 --> 01:02:09.260
did you see them
doing it differently,

01:02:09.260 --> 01:02:13.840
do you see this agenda
being more important

01:02:13.840 --> 01:02:15.640
for like the smaller countries

01:02:15.640 --> 01:02:17.940
or perhaps other
larger countries?

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:24.170
&gt;&gt; Cynthia P. Schneider: Well,
I might tie an answer to that

01:02:24.170 --> 01:02:30.650
into coming back to the
other Cynthia's question

01:02:30.650 --> 01:02:35.500
when you were asking about
culture kind of softening,

01:02:35.500 --> 01:02:38.850
softening the ground and I think

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:42.930
that there is also this
entity called public diplomacy

01:02:42.930 --> 01:02:47.540
which is different from
cultural diplomacy, particularly

01:02:47.540 --> 01:02:51.840
as hearing about it
practiced here and the larger

01:02:51.840 --> 01:02:53.360
in the United States
State Department,

01:02:53.360 --> 01:02:56.620
the largest bureau
is public diplomacy

01:02:56.620 --> 01:02:59.960
with the mission really of
promoting the understanding

01:02:59.960 --> 01:03:03.370
and acceptance of
America's policies,

01:03:03.370 --> 01:03:08.480
which is think is a fabulous
idea from the 1950's and not

01:03:08.480 --> 01:03:13.000
so appropriate now in this
age of global communications

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.970
and fortunately, you
can talk about this more

01:03:15.970 --> 01:03:19.690
but I have the sense that the
way cultural diplomacy operates

01:03:19.690 --> 01:03:22.850
is more in the way
of cultural relations

01:03:22.850 --> 01:03:26.880
and interestingly enough,
the British have gotten rid

01:03:26.880 --> 01:03:30.130
of the word cultural
diplomacy, and just talk

01:03:30.130 --> 01:03:31.660
about cultural relations.

01:03:31.660 --> 01:03:35.590
I think to avoid the
idea of what you said,

01:03:35.590 --> 01:03:40.740
that this is not a kind of
backdoor way into getting you

01:03:40.740 --> 01:03:44.910
to accept what other nefarious
policy we want you to accept

01:03:44.910 --> 01:03:47.640
so while you're up watching a
science movie we're doing this,

01:03:47.640 --> 01:03:53.690
and you know, and even, and
cultural diplomacy is a term

01:03:53.690 --> 01:03:58.480
which I've used a lot, I'm
increasingly troubled with it

01:03:58.480 --> 01:04:02.860
because it has that kind
of sense of, I have a goal

01:04:02.860 --> 01:04:05.800
and I'm going to use
this to get to that goal,

01:04:05.800 --> 01:04:09.150
but I think what you've heard
today is much more in the nature

01:04:09.150 --> 01:04:14.360
of cultural relations and
cultural exchange, whatever,

01:04:14.360 --> 01:04:17.050
you know, whatever
it might be called.

01:04:17.050 --> 01:04:21.370
I've seen some examples, I
think that I really admire

01:04:21.370 --> 01:04:27.410
that are more in the way of this
leveraging local voices idea,

01:04:27.410 --> 01:04:29.800
and it is often the
smaller countries,

01:04:29.800 --> 01:04:33.910
although Great Britain has bee
doing this for a long time and,

01:04:33.910 --> 01:04:37.100
you know, the whole structure is
different with other countries

01:04:37.100 --> 01:04:40.670
where they tend to, Great
Britain, France, Italy, Spain,

01:04:40.670 --> 01:04:43.450
they all have, Scandinavian
countries,

01:04:43.450 --> 01:04:47.380
they all have a slightly
separate arm's length division

01:04:47.380 --> 01:04:53.360
that takes care of culture and
so, they're a little bit less,

01:04:53.360 --> 01:04:56.040
in my experience, I'm sure
there's some exceptions to this,

01:04:56.040 --> 01:04:57.600
but there may be
a little bit less

01:04:57.600 --> 01:05:00.770
about promoting their
culture per se

01:05:00.770 --> 01:05:03.760
as leveraging local cultures.

01:05:03.760 --> 01:05:06.480
I saw for example a fantastic,
no you don't think so,

01:05:06.480 --> 01:05:09.230
well I'll just give you a couple
of examples that I have seen,

01:05:09.230 --> 01:05:14.480
they may not do it all the time,
but a fantastic hip hop event

01:05:14.480 --> 01:05:19.550
that the Scandinavians did in
Alexandria in Egypt bringing,

01:05:19.550 --> 01:05:24.090
you know, providing a stage and
a platform and the opportunity

01:05:24.090 --> 01:05:28.480
to perform to local hip hop
groups, which they don't have

01:05:28.480 --> 01:05:31.750
but that's what they want, to be
able to reach their audiences.

01:05:31.750 --> 01:05:35.350
At the same time, the way
this may have changed,

01:05:35.350 --> 01:05:37.340
this was about six
or seven years ago,

01:05:37.340 --> 01:05:39.560
at the same time the
United States policy was

01:05:39.560 --> 01:05:42.250
to send American
artists to places,

01:05:42.250 --> 01:05:44.710
so those are two
different approaches.

01:05:44.710 --> 01:05:47.910
I'll give one other example that
I think was really brilliant,

01:05:47.910 --> 01:05:51.210
which is what Great Britain
did during the Olympics

01:05:51.210 --> 01:05:55.780
with Shakespeare and it was
a fantastic way, I think,

01:05:55.780 --> 01:05:59.330
of showing how global
Shakespeare is and that is

01:05:59.330 --> 01:06:03.730
that they invited performances
of different Shakespeare plays

01:06:03.730 --> 01:06:07.130
in local languages
and in local idioms

01:06:07.130 --> 01:06:09.800
and they were performed
every night at the Globe.

01:06:09.800 --> 01:06:12.600
And you know, I don't know
who assigned the plays,

01:06:12.600 --> 01:06:14.920
it was kind of weird, like
China had Richard the Third

01:06:14.920 --> 01:06:18.010
and of all things, Pakistan
had the Taming of the Shrew.

01:06:18.010 --> 01:06:19.780
So, there were some odd things,

01:06:19.780 --> 01:06:23.690
but the plays were really
incredible and what a way,

01:06:23.690 --> 01:06:26.690
you know, without saying,
Shakespeare is global,

01:06:26.690 --> 01:06:32.210
it just came out through
all the performances.

01:06:32.210 --> 01:06:34.900
&gt;&gt; Amy Storrow: I would say
